VERDICT: not-confirmed
REASON: The finding describes caller-precondition misuse, not a kernel bug. Upstream Zephyr kernel/cpu_mask.c:15 carries BUILD_ASSERT(CONFIG_MP_MAX_NUM_CPUS <= 16) and thread.h:114 defines cpu_mask as uint16_t; together these establish the caller contract that cpu indices passed to k_thread_cpu_mask_enable/disable/pin must satisfy cpu < CONFIG_MP_MAX_NUM_CPUS <= 16. The gale shim in zephyr/gale_cpu_mask.c is byte-for-byte equivalent to upstream (BIT(cpu) with no bounds check in enable/disable/non-PIN_ONLY pin, u32→u16 narrowing on store) — it preserves upstream semantics and introduces no regression. CM4 is scoped to the cpu_mask_mod return value in the u32 model; it never claims an end-to-end property about the uint16_t TCB field, so there is no proof-code drift — only an incorrect reinterpretation of CM4's stated postcondition. Per the interestingness filter, this violates a caller precondition documented by upstream (BUILD_ASSERT and the uint16_t field width), which the procedure lists as a disqualifier. Additionally, safety/stpa/ucas.yaml does not exist; the STPA artifact at artifacts/stpa.yaml explicitly scopes UCAs as out-of-scope (file header, line 12-13), so no UCA mapping is possible regardless of verdict. No Verus/Kani oracle was run because the underlying defect claim fails inspection: the strengthened ensures `result.mask < (1<<16)` is not a property gale asserts, and rejecting it would be expected behavior, not a bug.
